  "prompt": "Why does my dog only lick me all over?",
  "response": "Dogs use licking as a form of communication and affection. If your dog is licking you all over, it could be expressing several things:\n\n1. **Affection**: Licking is often a way for dogs to show love and bonding. It's similar to how they might groom or show affection to other dogs.\n\n2. **Attention-seeking**: Your dog may have learned that licking gets your attention. If you respond positively to the licking, your dog might do it more often.\n\n3. **Taste**: Dogs have a strong sense of smell and taste, and they might be licking you because they like the taste of your skin, sweat, or any food residue.\n\n4. **Curiosity**: Dogs explore the world with their mouths, so your dog might just be curious about you and finding out more through licking.\n\n5. **Comfort and Stress Relief**: Licking can be a self-soothing behavior for dogs. If your dog is feeling anxious or stressed, they may lick you for comfort.\n\n6. **Communication**: In a dog's body language, licking can be a sign of submission or respect towards their owner.\n\nIf the licking becomes excessive or seems compulsive, it might be worth consulting a veterinarian or a dog behaviorist to rule out any underlying stress or medical issues.",
